ok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Burton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a placename that is very common in central and northern England. The derivation in most cases is from Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fort’ (see   Burke  ) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","French (northeastern): regional variant of   Berton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Burke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Siobhan, Aileen, Brennan, Brigid, Donovan, Liam, Murphy, Ulick, Aidan, Dermot.","English and Irish (of Anglo-Norman origin): habitational name from Burgh (Castle) in Suffolk, England. <i>Burk</i> represents an Anglo-Norman pronunciation of Old English <i>burg</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘fortification’ (see   Burgh  ).","German: variant of   Burk  ."]},{"name":"Burtin","meanings":["English: variant of   Burton  .","French (eastern): regional variant of   Bertin  ."]},{"name":"Borton","meanings":["English: variant of   Burton  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":43,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter de Burton was born about 1285, in Fylde, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger De Burton, was 16 and his mother, Mrs. Roger de Burton, was 11. He married Mrs Alice De Burton Of Stratford. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1335, in Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1285–about 1335":"umbes 1285–umbes 1335","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1335–1355":"1335–1355","1270–1290":"1270–1290","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","from 1307 to 1327":"1307 kuni 1327","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","about 1317":"umbes 1317","1355":"1355","about 1335":"umbes 1335","about 1285":"umbes 1285","1328":"1328","1317":